In[3]:
def df_column_uniquify(df):
    '''
    renames columns that are the same
    '''
    df_columns = df.columns
    new_columns = []
    for item in df_columns:
        counter = 0
        newitem = item
        while newitem in new_columns:
            counter += 1
            newitem = "{}_{}".format(item, counter)
        new_columns.append(newitem)
    df.columns = new_columns
    return df
In[4]:
def abbr_to_isoalpha3(abbr):
    """
    Convert a European country ISO Alpha-2 code to ISO Alpha-3 code.

    Parameters:
        abbreviation (str): ISO Alpha-2 country code (e.g., 'DE' for Germany).

    Returns:
        str: ISO Alpha-3 country code (e.g., 'DEU'), or None if not found.
    """
    try:
        country = pycountry.countries.get(alpha_2=abbr.upper())
        if country:
            return country.alpha_3
        else:
            return None
    except KeyError:
        return None

    "BE": "Belgium",

    "GE": "Georgia",
    "AL": "Albania",
    "RS": "Serbia",
    "AD": "Andorra",
    "AM": "Armenia"
}

def abbr_to_name(abbreviation):
    return country_dict.get(abbreviation.upper(), "Abbreviation not found")

def name_to_abbr(name):
    reverse_dict = {v: k for k, v in country_dict.items()}
    return reverse_dict.get(name.title(), "Country name not found")

Death Data

In this section, we import and clean the death data to prepare it for analysis.

Source

  • Eurostat Database

Downloading Instructions

  1. Visit the source link.
  2. Click "Download" and select the spreadsheet format.
  3. Confirm the download to obtain the data.

Description

This dataset contains the weekly count of deaths in European countries between 2015 and 2024 (up to approximately week 47).

Variables

  • dd: Base dataframe for the death data.
  • ddy: dd grouped by year.
  • ddr2023: Death data ranked by deaths in 2023.
  • ddr2024: Death data ranked by deaths in 2024.

Import and Cleaning

This step involves loading the death data and preparing it for analysis by addressing issues such as missing values, inconsistent formatting, and unnecessary columns.

# getting the data 
dd = pd.read_excel(os.path.join(DataDIR,"demo_r_mwk_ts__custom_14738200_page_spreadsheet.xlsx"),sheet_name = "Sheet 1")

# remove the headers
dd = dd.iloc[7:47]

# drop the bad columns
for c in dd.columns:
    if pd.isnull(dd.at[7,c]):
        dd = dd.drop(columns=[c])

# rename time columns
for c in dd.columns:
    name = dd.at[7,c]
    dd = dd.rename(columns={c: name})

# make the duplicate column names unique
dd = df_column_uniquify(dd)

# # rename the first two columns
dd = dd.rename(columns={'TIME': 'abbr'})
dd = dd.rename(columns={'TIME_1':'name'})
           
# drop, replace, reset index,
dd = dd.drop([7,8,9])
dd = dd.replace(to_replace=':', value=None)
dd = dd.reset_index(drop=True)

In[7]:
# This code processes the raw death data (dd) by restructuring it into a long-form dataframe. 
# Each row in the new dataframe represents a single country's deaths for a specific year and week, 
# along with additional metadata such as country abbreviations and derived values.

yw_cols = dd.columns[2::]
abbrs = dd.abbr.drop_duplicates().to_list()
names = dd.name.drop_duplicates().to_list()
d = []

for ic,c in enumerate(abbrs):
    for yw in yw_cols:
        y = yw[0:4]
        w = yw[6:8]
        dv = dd.at[ic,yw]
            
        d.append(
            {
                'name': names[ic],
                'abbr':c,
                'year':y,
                'week':w,
                'year.week': int(y) + int(w)/100,
                'year.p': int(y) + (int(w)/53.001),
                'deaths': dv
            }
        )

#print(d)
dd = pd.DataFrame(d)
dd.year = pd.to_numeric(dd.year)
dd.week = pd.to_numeric(dd.week)
display(dd.head(10))
display(dd.tail(10))

# there are quite a few NAN (not a number) values
# here we get rid of them 

# Get counts of NA values for each 'abbr' group
na_counts = dd[dd.deaths.isna()].groupby('abbr').size()

# Filter for 'abbr' groups with more than 12 NA values
filtered_abbrs = na_counts[na_counts > 12].index

for c in filtered_abbrs:
    print(f'removing -- {c} {abbr_to_name(c)} NACount={na_counts[c]}')
    dd = dd[dd.abbr != c]  # Drop rows where 'abbr' matches

In[10]:
# Fill missing values (NaNs) in the 2024 data with the mean deaths for 2024 by country

# Filter data for the year 2024
df_2024 = dd[dd.year == 2024]

# Group the 2024 data by country abbreviation ('abbr') and calculate summary statistics
grouped = df_2024.groupby('abbr')

# Compute statistics: mean, total count, number of NaNs, total deaths, and mean deaths per week
stats = grouped['deaths'].agg(
    Mean='mean',          # Average deaths for each country in 2024
    Count='size',         # Total number of records for each country in 2024
    NACount=lambda x: x.isna().sum(),  # Count of missing (NaN) values
    SumFor2024='sum'      # Total deaths for each country in 2024
).reset_index()

# Replace missing death values in 2024 with the calculated mean for each country
for _, row in stats.iterrows():
    dd.loc[
        (dd.abbr == row['abbr']) & (dd.year == 2024) & (dd.deaths.isna()), 
        'deaths'
    ] = row['Mean']
In[11]:
# here we normalize the death values

dd['deaths_norm'] = 0.0

## baseline years are 2015,2016,2017 before the pandemic 
blyears = dd[dd.year.isin([2015,2016,2017])]
grouped = blyears.groupby('abbr')

temp = grouped['deaths'].agg(
    baseline='mean',
).reset_index()

for _, row in temp.iterrows():
    dd.loc[dd.abbr == row['abbr'], 'deaths_norm'] = dd[(dd.abbr == row['abbr'])].deaths / row['baseline']

Observations

The recovery from the COVID-19 pandemic varies significantly across countries. What factors might explain these differences?

Hypothesis

Based on reports such as:

  • U.S. COVID Deaths Are Rising Again. Experts Call It A 'Pandemic Of The Unvaccinated'
  • CDC Warns of 'Pandemic of the Unvaccinated'

Could countries with lower vaccination rates also be struggling more to recover from the pandemic?
Lets test this hypothesis.

Vaccine Data

Source

  • Vaccine Tracker
  • Data Download: Download the dataset in CSV format.

Description

This dataset provides detailed information on COVID-19 vaccinations within the EU/EEA, as collected through The European Surveillance System (TESSy). It includes indicators such as:

  • Number of vaccine doses distributed by manufacturers.
  • Number of first, second, additional, and unspecified doses administered.
  • Data categorized by target groups at the national level.

Key Notes:

  • Member States report data every four weeks.
  • Retrospective corrections are applied, and updated datasets are released regularly.
  • Data usage is subject to ECDCs copyright policy.

Variables

  • vd: Base vaccine dataset.
  • vdr2023: Vaccination data ranked by the cumulative sum for 2023.
  • vdravg: Vaccination data ranked by the average cumulative sum for 2020, 2021, 2022, and 2023.

Import and Cleaning

This step involves loading the death data and preparing it for analysis by addressing issues such as missing values, inconsistent formatting, and unnecessary columns.

In[21]:
# i only care about the total vaccines (not broken into Age group)
vd = vd[vd.TargetGroup == 'ALL']
vd =vd.drop(columns=['TargetGroup'])

# calculate the sum of all the Doses
vd = pd.pivot_table(
    data = vd,
    values = ['FirstDose','SecondDose','DoseAdditional1','DoseAdditional2','DoseAdditional3','DoseAdditional4','DoseAdditional5','UnknownDose'],
    index = ['ReportingCountry','YearWeekISO','Population'],
    aggfunc="sum"
    )
vd = vd.reset_index()

# convert to a number 
vd['year'] = pd.to_numeric(vd['YearWeekISO'].str[0:4])
vd['week'] = pd.to_numeric(vd['YearWeekISO'].str[6:8])
vd['year.week'] = vd['year'] + (vd['week']/100.0)
vd['year.p'] = vd['year'] + (vd['week']/53.001)

vd = vd.rename(columns={'ReportingCountry':'abbr'})
vd['name'] = vd.abbr.apply(abbr_to_name)

# gets get the total doses given 
doseCol = ['FirstDose','SecondDose','DoseAdditional1','DoseAdditional2','DoseAdditional3','DoseAdditional4','DoseAdditional5','UnknownDose']
vd['total_dose'] = vd[doseCol].sum(axis=1)

# # lets get the doses as a percent of the population
vd['total_dose_ratio'] = vd['total_dose']/vd['Population']
vd['1_does_ratio'] = vd['FirstDose']/vd['Population']
vd['2_does_ratio'] = vd['SecondDose']/vd['Population']
vd = vd.drop(columns=doseCol)

# Calculate cumulative sum for each column, grouped by 'abbr'
vd['td_cumsum'] = vd.groupby('abbr')['total_dose_ratio'].cumsum()
vd['1d_cumsum'] = vd.groupby('abbr')['1_does_ratio'].cumsum()
vd['2d_cumsum'] = vd.groupby('abbr')['2_does_ratio'].cumsum()

# lets drop the columns we don't need anymore 
vd = vd.drop(columns=['YearWeekISO'])

# filling unknown values with 0.0
vd = vd.fillna(0.0)

Overlap Analysis

This section compares the top and bottom-ranked countries by deaths and vaccinations in 2023. The analysis checks for overlaps in the following scenarios:

  1. Top-ranked deaths vs. top-ranked vaccinations.
  2. Bottom-ranked deaths vs. bottom-ranked vaccinations.
  3. Top-ranked deaths vs. bottom-ranked vaccinations.
  4. Bottom-ranked deaths vs. top-ranked vaccinations.

The results provide insights into potential relationships between vaccination rates and death counts across countries.

Correlation Analysis

This section analyzes the relationship between two ranked datasets:

  1. Death data ranks (ddr2024).
  2. Vaccination data ranks (vdr2023).

The ranks are compared to identify similarities in their ordering using two statistical methods: Spearman's Rank Correlation and Kendall's Tau.

Steps:

  1. Preprocessing:

    • The death data (ddr2024) and vaccination data (vdr2023) are copied and reset to ensure a clean comparison.
    • Irrelevant columns (e.g., yearly data) are removed, keeping only the relevant ranking information.
    • Data from both datasets are filtered to include only matching country abbreviations (abbr).

  2. Rank Alignment:

    • Vaccination ranks from vdr2023 are assigned to the corresponding countries in the death data (ddr2024), ensuring both datasets are aligned for comparison.

  3. Output Interpretation: A summary of the correlation output is provided:

    • 1: Indicates strong similarity in the order of ranks.
    • -1: Indicates a strong inverse relationship in ranks.
    • 0: Suggests no correlation in the order.

  4. Statistical Methods:

    • Spearman's Rank Correlation: Measures the strength and direction of the monotonic relationship between two ranked variables.
      • Range: -1 (perfect inverse) to 1 (perfect similarity).
      • Use Case: Detects whether higher ranks in one dataset correspond to higher ranks in the other (or inversely).
    • Kendall's Tau: Measures the strength of association between two ranked variables based on concordant and discordant pairs.
      • Range: -1 (perfect inverse) to 1 (perfect similarity).
      • Use Case: Evaluates rank agreement between two datasets, factoring in the proportion of pairwise agreements.

Outputs:

  • Spearman's Rank Correlation: Reflects how well the relationship between the rankings can be described as monotonic.
  • Kendall's Tau: Provides a stricter measure of rank agreement, focusing on pairwise comparisons.

The results help assess whether vaccination rates and death rates have a correlated ordering across countries.

In[31]:
d = ddr2024.copy().reset_index()
d = d.rename(columns={'index':'value'})
d = d.drop(columns=[2015,2016,2017,2018,2019,2020,2021,2022,2023,2024])
# d['rank'] = d['value'].rank()

v = vdr2023.copy().reset_index()
v = v.rename(columns={'index':'value'})
v = v.drop(columns=[2020,2021,2022,2023])
v['rank'] = v['value'].rank()


d = d[d.abbr.isin(v.abbr)]

for i, row in v.iterrows():
    d.loc[d['abbr']==row['abbr'], 'rank'] = row['rank']

# display(d)
# display(v)


display(MD(
'''### Output Interpretation
* 1  : indicates high similarity in order.
* -1 : indicates inverse order.
* 0  : suggests no similarity in order.
'''
))

# Calculate Spearman's Rank Correlation
spearman_corr, _ = spearmanr(d['rank'], v['rank'])
display(MD(f"Spearman's Rank Correlation: {spearman_corr}"))

# Calculate Kendall's Tau
kendall_corr, _ = kendalltau(d['rank'], v['rank'])
display(MD(f"Kendall's Tau: {kendall_corr}"))

Output Interpretation

  • 1 : indicates high similarity in order.
  • -1 : indicates inverse order.
  • 0 : suggests no similarity in order.

Spearman's Rank Correlation: 0.23515016685205786

Kendall's Tau: 0.1632183908045977

list comparison

below is a way to visualize the comparison between the deaths and vaccines.

on the left is a list of the countries from lest deaths to most deaths in 2023.
on the right is a list of the countries from most vaccinated to least vaccinated in 2023.
the more horizontal the line the darker the color, and the more vertical the line the lighter the color.

In[32]:
d = ddr2023.copy().reset_index()
d = d.rename(columns={'index':'value'})
d = d.drop(columns=[2015,2016,2017,2018,2019,2020,2021,2022,2023,2024])
# d['rank'] = d['value'].rank()

v = vdr2023.copy().reset_index()
v = v.rename(columns={'index':'value'})
v = v.drop(columns=[2020,2021,2022,2023])
v['rank'] = v['value'].rank()


d = d[d.abbr.isin(v.abbr)]

for i, row in v.iterrows():
    d.loc[d['abbr']==row['abbr'], 'rank'] = row['rank']

d = d.reset_index(drop=True)

# display(d)
# display(v)

# Create a plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 7))

ydistance = 0.95

# Plot points for the first dataframe
for i, row in d.iterrows():
    ax.scatter(0, i * ydistance, label=row['name'], color='blue')
    ax.text(-0.025, i * ydistance, row['name'] + ': ' + str(row['value']), ha='right', va='center', color='blue')

# Plot points for the second dataframe
for i, row in v.iterrows():
    ax.scatter(1, i * ydistance, label=row['name'], color='red')
    ax.text(1.025, i * ydistance, row['name'] + ': ' + str(row['value']), ha='left', va='center', color='red')


# Create a colormap
colormap = plt.get_cmap('magma')
norm = Normalize(vmin=-np.pi, vmax=np.pi)

# Draw lines connecting matching abbr values
for name in d['name']:
    if name in v['name'].values:
        idx1 = d[d['name'] == name].index[0] * ydistance
        idx2 = v[v['name'] == name].index[0] * ydistance
        ax.plot([0, 1], [idx1, idx2], color='gray', linestyle='-')
        vertical_diff = idx2 - idx1
        horizontal_diff = 1  # The horizontal distance between the columns
        angle = np.arctan2(vertical_diff, horizontal_diff)  # Calculate the angle

        # normalized_angle = (angle + 2 * np.pi) / (2 * np.pi )  # Normalize angle to [0, 1]
        normalized_angle = pow ( abs(angle / np.pi)/0.5, 3) # custom normalized angle for better colors
        # print(normalized_angle)

        color = colormap(normalized_angle)  # Map normalized angle to a color
        ax.plot([0, 1], [idx1, idx2], color=color, linestyle='-')

# Formatting
ax.set_xlim(-0.5, 1.5)
ax.set_ylim(-1, max(len(d), len(v)))
ax.set_xticks([0, 1])
ax.set_xticklabels(['deaths 2023', 'vaccines 2023'])
ax.set_yticks([])
ax.set_title('Mapping Between deaths and vaccines\n low values at the top, high values at the bottom')
ax.grid(False)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Viewing Merged Data

This section presents various charts, graphs, and plots to visualize the relationship between death data and vaccination data. These visualizations aim to explore potential correlations and trends, helping to identify patterns in the data.

Objectives:

  1. Highlight any correlations between vaccination rates and death rates.
  2. Compare rankings of countries based on deaths and vaccinations.
  3. Provide insights into how vaccination efforts may influence death rates across countries.

The visualizations will include scatter plots, rank comparisons, and other statistical representations to facilitate interpretation of the merged data.

In[34]:
title = 'Line Chart - Deaths Normalized and Total Doses 2015-2024 (by week)'
display(MD(f'### {title}'))
report = r"docs\md_line.html"


md = md.sort_values(by=['abbr','year.p'])

fig = px.line(
    md,
    x='year.p',
    y=['deaths_norm','total_dose_ratio'],
    color='name',
    height=750,
    title= title
    )
fig.update_layout(template="plotly_dark")

fig.add_shape(
    type="line",
    x0=2015.00, x1=2024.99,
    y0=1, y1=1, # Start and end y-coordinates
    line=dict(color="Red", width=2, dash="dash"),  # Line style
    xref="x", yref="y"          # Reference axes
)

pio.write_html(fig, file=report, auto_open=True)

display(FileLink(report))
display(MD('[weblink](https://jgarza9788.github.io/Excess_Mortality_And_Vaccines_In_Europe/md_line.html)'))

fig.show()

temp = md.copy()
temp = temp[(temp.year >= 2020.00) & (temp.year <= 2023.999)]

temp = pd.pivot_table(
    data = temp,
    values = ['deaths_norm','total_dose_ratio'],
    index = ['abbr','name','year.p'],
    # aggfunc="sum"
)
temp = temp.reset_index()
temp['hue'] = 0.0
for _, row in ddr2023.iterrows():
    temp.loc[temp.abbr == row['abbr'], 'hue'] = _

sns.scatterplot(
    data=temp, 
    x="total_dose_ratio", 
    y="deaths_norm",
    hue='hue',
    edgecolor="black",
    palette='Spectral',
    legend=False
    )

sns.rugplot(
    data=temp, 
    x="total_dose_ratio",
    y="deaths_norm", 
    height=.05,
    hue='hue',
    palette='Spectral',
    legend=False
    )

# Add a title

In[41]:
temp = md.copy()
temp = temp[(temp.year >= 2023.00) & (temp.year <= 2023.999)]

temp = pd.pivot_table(
    data = temp,
    values = ['deaths_norm','total_dose_ratio'],
    index = ['abbr','name','year.p'],
    # aggfunc="sum"
)
temp = temp.reset_index()

## by powering the values it might be easier to see the correlation
#temp.deaths_norm = pow(temp.deaths_norm,2.0)
#temp.total_dose_ratio = pow(temp.total_dose_ratio,2.0) 

temp['hue'] = 0.0

for n, row in ddr2023.iterrows():
    h = 0.0
    if n <= 10.0:
        h = 1.0
    if n >= 20.0:
        h = -1.0
    temp.loc[temp.abbr == row['abbr'], 'hue'] = h

sns.scatterplot(
    data=temp, 
    x="total_dose_ratio", 
    y="deaths_norm",
    hue='hue',
    edgecolor="black",
    palette='Spectral'
    )

sns.rugplot(
    data=temp, 
    x="total_dose_ratio",
    y="deaths_norm", 
    height=.05,
    hue='hue',
    palette='Spectral',
    legend=False
    )

# Add a title
plt.title("ScatterPlot - deaths and total vaccine doses (2023)\nhue based on 2023 deaths", fontsize=16)

# Add vertical and horizontal lines
plt.axvline(x=0.0, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)  # Vertical line at x=20
plt.axhline(y=1.0, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)  # Horizontal line at y=3

plt.show()

note:

  • this plot's colors are based on the 2023 deaths, but we groupped them slow deaths, medium deaths, and high deaths
  • we can see on the X axis there are fewer high deaths at the 0.0 total_dose_ratio
In[42]:
temp = md.copy()
temp = temp[(temp.year >= 2023.00) & (temp.year <= 2023.999)]

temp = pd.pivot_table(
    data = temp,
    values = ['deaths_norm','total_dose_ratio'],
    index = ['abbr','name','year.p'],
    # aggfunc="sum"
)
temp = temp.reset_index()
temp['hue'] = 0.0

for _, row in ddr2023.iterrows():
    temp.loc[temp.abbr == row['abbr'], 'hue'] = _


for nums in [[0,10],[10,20],[20,30]]:

    temp2 =  temp[(temp.hue >= nums[0]) & (temp.hue <= nums[1])]

    sns.scatterplot(
        data=temp2, 
        x="total_dose_ratio", 
        y="deaths_norm",
        # hue='hue',
        edgecolor="black",
        # palette='Spectral',
        legend=False
        )

    sns.rugplot(
        data=temp2, 
        x="total_dose_ratio",
        y="deaths_norm", 
        height=.05,
        # hue='hue',
        # palette='Spectral',
        legend=False
        )

    # Add a title
    plt.title(f"ScatterPlot - deaths and total vaccine doses (2023)\n2023 deaths ranked {nums[0]} to {nums[1]}", fontsize=16)

    # Set axis ranges
    plt.xlim(- 0.001, 0.014)  # Set x-axis range from 0 to 6
    plt.ylim(0.5, 2.0) # Set y-axis range from 5 to 55

    # Add vertical and horizontal lines
    plt.axvline(x=0.0, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)  # Vertical line at x=20
    plt.axhline(y=1.0, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=1)  # Horizontal line at y=3

    plt.show()

note:

  • in the plots above the death groups are broken in there own plot
  • notice that the last plot much lower deaths and vaccines

Conclusion

with a Spearman Rank Correlation of ~0.2352 and a Kendall's Tau of ~0.1632 there is definitely a positive correlation between the amount of vaccines a country took and the amount deaths those countries have experienced, and how those countries death rate has not bounced back to normal.

the most vaccinated countries have the most deaths, which is the opposite from the hypothesis above.

However this correlation is week, how can we make it stronger.

  • filter out the deaths of old people (since there death might not be related to the vaccine)
  • filter only by specific deaths (heart attack, stroke, and other blood and Circular Vascular related issues)

I would like to make a note of this:

  • shouldn't we see the opposite correlation... where the most vaccinated countries have fewer deaths ?
